\begin_layout Standard
The population is size 1.
 There is a single binary genetic trait and a single social trait.
 Individuals 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 thus have 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}\in\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}\in\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

; write 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}=(G_{i},S_{i})$
\end_inset

 to fully describe 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's type.
 We will call individuals with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}=(1,1),(1,0),(0,1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,0)$
\end_inset

, b-types, g-types, s-types and n-types respectively.
 The proportion of the population with 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, and the population proportion with 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{t},g_{t},s_{t},n_{t}$
\end_inset

 for the population proportion of each type in generation 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1,2,....$
\end_inset

 Sometimes we drop the subscript.
 Initially, 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

 are independent, so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
b_{1} & =\gamma\sigma;\\
g_{1} & =\gamma(1-\sigma);\\
s_{1} & =(1-\gamma)\sigma;\\
n_{1} & =(1-\gamma)(1-\sigma).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Higher values are assumed to be more attractive in the marriage market.
 Indeed, individuals are divided into two classes, 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, for the purpose of marital matching.
 Within 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, all individuals form spouse pairs at random.
 Class 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is of size 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

: we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\sigma<\theta<\min\{\gamma,\sigma\}$
\end_inset

.
 Married pairs have two children and each randomly inherits one parent's
 genetic trait and one parent's social trait.
 As a result, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 stay constant over generations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
B-types with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}=(1,1)$
\end_inset

 are always in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 N-types with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}=(0,0)$
\end_inset

 are always in 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 Where the other groups fit depends on the nature of the society.
 Of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\equiv\theta-\gamma\sigma$
\end_inset

 non-b-types in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, a proportion 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 are s-types and the remaining 
\begin_inset Formula $1-k$
\end_inset

 are g-types.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To build intuition, we start with two extreme examples.
 Suppose first that 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 This is a 
\emph on
caste society
\emph default
 where marital matching is entirely driven by social status.
 All individuals in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $L)$
\end_inset

 have 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}=0$
\end_inset

), and so do their children.
 On the other hand, the proportion of individuals with 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 stays at 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 within both groups.
 Thus, over generations, the distributions of 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

 remain independent in the populatoin.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose next that 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 This society is 
\emph on
socially egalitarian
\emph default
: only genetics matter for marital matching.
 All individuals in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $L)$
\end_inset

 have 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}=0$
\end_inset

), and so do their children.
 The proportion of individuals with 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 stays at 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 within both groups; hence, again, 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

 remain independent over generations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In between these cases, 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

 will become positively correlated.
 Within either group 
\begin_inset Formula $J\in\{H,L\}$
\end_inset

, write the proportion of types in the parents generation as 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{J},g_{J},s_{J},n_{J}$
\end_inset

 for the respective types.
 
\end_layout

