\begin_layout Standard
Summing these in each group, and using that 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{H}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{L}=0$
\end_inset

, gives the proportion of children of each type (
\begin_inset Formula $b_{H}^{c}$
\end_inset

 etc.)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
b_{J}^{c} & =b_{J}+\rho_{J}\\
g_{J}^{c} & =g_{J}-\rho_{J}\\
s_{J}^{c} & =s_{J}-\rho_{J}\\
n_{J}^{c} & =n_{J}+\rho_{J}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{J}\equiv\frac{1}{2}g_{J}s_{J}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, when a group contains both g-types and s-types, some of
 them marry each other and produce some b- and n-types.
 This increases the correlation between 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Summing over the groups we can write the new generation's proportion of
 types in the whole population as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
b^{c} & =b+\rho\\
g^{c} & =g-\rho\\
s^{c} & =s-\rho\\
n^{c} & =n+\rho
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho\equiv\theta\rho_{H}+(1-\theta)\rho_{L}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the first generation, we can calculate:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
b_{H} & =\gamma\sigma/\theta;\\
g_{H} & =(1-k)\phi/\theta\\
s_{H} & =k\phi/\theta;\\
n_{H} & =0;
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
b_{L} & =0;\\
g_{L} & =\frac{\gamma(1-\sigma)-\phi(1-k)}{1-\theta}\\
s_{L} & =\frac{(1-\gamma)\sigma-\phi k}{1-\theta}\\
n_{L} & =\frac{(1-\gamma)(1-\sigma)}{1-\theta};
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and from these
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\rho_{H} & =\frac{1}{2}\frac{\phi^{2}k(1-k)}{\theta^{2}};\\
\rho_{L} & =\frac{1}{2}\frac{[\gamma(1-\sigma)-\phi(1-k)][(1-\gamma)\sigma-\phi k]}{(1-\theta)^{2}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\rho= & \frac{1}{2}\frac{\phi^{2}k(1-k)}{\theta}+\\
 & \frac{1}{2}\frac{[\gamma(1-\sigma)-\phi(1-k)][(1-\gamma)\sigma-\phi k]}{(1-\theta)}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now calculate the covariance between 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 in the second generation.
 The covariance is just 
\begin_inset Formula $E(G_{i}S_{i})-E(G_{i})E(S_{i})$
\end_inset

; in general, at generation 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, this is 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{t}-\gamma\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $t=2$
\end_inset

 this is just equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that when 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\sigma$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 evaluates to 0.
 Similarly, when 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\gamma$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 evaluates to 0.
 This confirms the claims we made above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is a quadratic in 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Differentiating 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{d\rho}{dk} & =\frac{1}{2\theta}\phi^{2}(1-2k)+\frac{1}{2(1-\theta)}[\phi^{2}(1-2k)+\phi(\sigma-\gamma)]\\
 & =\frac{1}{2\theta(1-\theta)}\phi^{2}(1-2k)+\frac{1}{2(1-\theta)}\phi(\sigma-\gamma)\\
 & =\frac{1}{2(1-\theta)}\left[\frac{\phi^{2}}{\theta}(1-2k)+\phi(\sigma-\gamma)\right].
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is decreasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is concave.
 We find the maximum by setting the term in square brackets to 0, giving:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\theta}{\theta-\gamma\sigma}(\sigma-\gamma).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This will be interior if 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is close enough to either 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, and if 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 are not too different.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lemma: The second-generation correlation 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

 is concave in 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is close enough to 
\begin_inset Formula $\min\{\sigma,\gamma\}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma<\gamma<\frac{1}{2}+\frac{\sigma}{2}\textrm{ or }\gamma<\sigma<\frac{1}{2}+\frac{\gamma}{2}
\]

\end_inset

then the correlation has a maximum in the interior of 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proof: First assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma<\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\rightarrow\sigma$
\end_inset

, the expression above approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{2}\frac{(\sigma-\gamma)}{(1-\gamma)}$
\end_inset

.
 The requirement for this to be interior is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\sigma-\gamma\right|<\left|1-\gamma\right|$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma<\gamma$
\end_inset

 this is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma<(1+\sigma)/2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma<\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\rightarrow\gamma$
\end_inset

, the expression approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{2}\frac{(\sigma-\gamma)}{(1-\sigma)}$
\end_inset

.
 This is interior when 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\sigma-\gamma\right|<\left|1-\sigma\right|$
\end_inset

, equivalently when 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma<(1+\gamma)/2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

